data.value:
Hydra is the largest of all the modern constellations, and has a long, complex history. This constellation spans almost the entirety of the night sky, being most visible in the month of April. Although it’s technically a southern hemisphere constellation, you can sometimes spot it from the northern hemisphere during April.
Many believe Hydra to represent a female water snake, with Hydrus in the southern hemisphere as its male counterpart. However, the most well-known myth of Hydra is that of Hercules’ twelve labors. The monster was a many-headed being who was slain by the mighty Hercules to complete one of his twelve labors. As the creature terrorized countless towns, Hercules tried to stop the nine-headed monster by slicing off it’s heads. However, any head cut off of the Hydra would just sprout two or three more. The only way Hercules was able to defeat it was by burning the stump left after cutting its head off, repeating this action until he finally overcame the massive beast.
